post_text: Today we welcomed Comgressman Antonio Delgado who wanted to hear first hand from our educators about how we are preparing to reopen schools this fall. We focused on the acute need for state & local funding to address budget shortages, access to PPE & testing & expanded rural broadband to facilitate remote learning as well as federal relief from academic standardized testing.

post_text:
Grade 5 Guided Tours

On August 24th, 25th, and 26th all incoming 5th grade students will be able to visit the middle school building. Guided tours will begin in the MS Lobby and run at 15 minute blocks of time between 8:30 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. Please call the middle school office to schedule a time slot for your child at (518) 731-1862. Office hours are Monday-Thursday, 7:30 a.m.-4:00 p.m. Please note that only students will be allowed in the building for this tour. A health screening assessment and temperature check is required to be completed before entering the school.

We look forward to seeing our incoming 5th grade students.

post_text: The Coxsackie-Athens Schools is saddened to hear of the passing of Wayne Parks. The district extends its condolences and prayers to his family and everyone who works at Coxsackie Transport. Wayne, through Coxsackie Transport, has been a long time partner with C-A in providing safe transportation for many of our students. His leadership in our community will be missed.

Greene County's self response rate for the 2020 Census lags far behind the rest of New York State and the United States. We all need to do a better job at getting our Census filled out. It is simple, easy and only takes a few minutes.

Visit my2020Census.gov now to fill out your Census form.

https://my2020census.gov/

The 2020 Census is critical. A complete and accurate count will help shape the future of our community and inform how hundreds of billions of dollars in federal funding are distributed for important programs and services in health care, emergency and disaster response, education, and infrastructure.

This map of response rates across the country shows what percentage of households in your community have responded. https://2020census.gov/en/response-rates.html?utm_campaign=20200717msc20s1ccallnl&utm_medium=email&utm_source=govdelivery

post_text:
2020-21 BUDGET PASSES:
Budget passes 1164 YES votes to 511 NO votes. A 70% approval. Thank you to everyone who voted. The 2nd time since 1984 our budget had a 70% or higher approval rate. This was the most total votes cast as far back as our records go. We appreciate the affirmation from our school community on the direction our district is taking to ensure every learner achieves extraordinary success.

BOE elections- top 3 will serve 3-year terms:
Tara Bachner: 914 votes
Kimberly Bushane: 543 votes
Jamie Dorr: 832 votes
James Ewing: 362 votes
Kyle Garland: 627 votes
Ina Griffin-Guilzon: 651 votes
William MacDonald: 458 votes
Viviana Tovar: 170 votes

Thank you to everyone who ran for the BOE.

post_text:
Dear Juniors & Seniors:

After communication from our representative at the Desmond, Mrs. Kearney and I have made the decision to cancel the 2020 Prom. Student safety is always our number one concern, and there is not currently a way to hold a dinner and dance that would allow us to maintain social distance. This is not a decision we took lightly, and we tried to maintain this important tradition for as long as we could.

We still have plans for a virtual coronation and welcome current Juniors to be involved in planning for prom next spring.

Mrs. Kearney and I are both very sorry and hope all of us can celebrate together next spring.

Sincerely yours,
Dr. Mercer

Paint the town BLUE & WHITE! If you live in the Coxsackie & Athens area and would like to show your support to this year's graduating class, the High School Student Council is working with A Few Guys Signs to help cover our towns in CA pride!

Please check out this link:
https://a-few-guys-signs-2.square.site/
to see the sign and place your order!

Signs and yard stakes can be sent directly to you or you can arrange for pickup / delivery.
In addition to your support from home - please know that a portion of each sign will help to fund a scholarship that will be awarded to a 2020 grad.
Thank you for your support and please feel free to share the link to any of your friends and family or on your personal social media so that we can cover the area in blue & white for our grads!

post_text:
YOU COUNT! Have you completed your 2020 census? Did you know both federal and state aid to our schools, towns and county are factored by census numbers? We've improved since April 24 but have a ways to go to match 2010 participation.
As of today the % of residents who have responded is:
New Baltimore: 37% up 3% since 4/24 (75% in 2010)
Coxsackie: 46% up 7% since 4/24 (66% in 2010)
Athens: 46% up 8% since 4/24(60% in 2010)
Cairo: 36% up 6% since 4/24(60 % in 2010)

Learn more by visiting our website and click on Census 2020 or Google Census 2020.
https://youtu.be/oXZAe8XYeNQ

post_text: EJA Marathon Time! The girls running club is hosting a virtual marathon. We would love it if you and your families would join us. What do you need to do? Well watch the video that Olivia and Gwen made and then print up the flyer from your teachers Google Classroom and start documenting your miles. Don't have a printer, no worries, just write it down on loose leaf. Don't forget to put your first and last name on the paper and your teacher's name. (Remember, there may be more than one person with your name in our school.) Have fun!

IMPORTANT AP TESTING INFORMATION
Coxsackie-Athens High School
Students taking AP exams should complete the AP Checklist and AP Exam Demo this week prior to exams (schedule below). Reviewing the full testing guide is strongly encouraged as well.
Info for students can be found here: https://apcoronavirusupdates.collegeboard.org/students

AP EXAM SCHEDULE
Students should check in to their exams to complete security checks 30 minutes prior to the exam time.
Tuesday, May 12 – Calculus AB – 2:00 p.m.
Wednesday, May 13 – English Lit & Comp – 2:00 p.m.
Friday, May 15 – U.S. History – 2:00 p.m.
Monday, May 18 – Biology – 2:00 p.m.
Tuesday, May 19 – Music Theory – 12 p.m.
Wednesday, May 20 – English Lang & Comp – 2 p.m.
Thursday, May 21 – World History – 2:00 p.m.

Graduation is scheduled for June 26, 2020. At this time, we are still planning to hold a traditional ceremony. We also have multiple alternatives that will depend on how many people are allowed to gather in one place at the end of June. Like last year, we plan to stream our ceremony and continue with our "enhanced" graduation program available online that includes pictures, video clips, and a more detailed listing of senior awards and scholarships.

Community members, friends, and family who are looking for additional ways to help celebrate the Class of 2020, please reach out to Mr. Carlson and Dr. Mercer. Staff are already working on some surprises, but we would love your ideas or help.

post_text:
CE RIDE THE WAVE PARADE (RAIN OR SHINE)
A parade is coming to town and you're the MAIN EVENT. On Friday, May 1st, we will have a 'reverse parade.'
Here's how it works:

Members of our CE Staff will be on campus on Friday, May 1st beginning at 10am.
Practicing social distancing, staff will be lined along the sidewalk in the bus loop and on Sunset Blvd.
Families are welcome to come to campus in their cars to wave to everyone.
While traveling along the parade route, no student or person should exit their car.

What a great way to celebrate Spring and of course all of you! We hope to see everyone on Friday, May 1st. We miss you!

post_text: Mrs. Pacuk has been gardening with her students via. distance learning. The greenhouse was set up in her basement. Using grow lights, she and students have been growing tomatoes, peppers, lettuce, basil, rosemary, parsley and marigolds. All of this is communicated through her remote learning site. In addition, she stopped over to the EJA garden the other day and under the cold frame found that our fall garden had re-seeded itself and has kohlrabi, garlic, lettuce and turnips growing in it.

post_text:
INTERNET ACCESS:
Mid-Hudson Cable is offering Standard Internet Service with a speed of 150mb for free to C-A students, including our current subscribers and non- subscribers for 60 days. In addition, customers with C-A students, who use our video service will be given an additional 10% discount on that service. Parents of C-A students must simply reach out to Mid-Hudson Cable or call the school office and let us know their Student’s name(s) and provide the proper documentation on what school they attend within the C-A school district.

• No Disconnects or Late Fees: We will not disconnect a customer’s internet service or assess late fees if they contact us and let us know that they can’t pay their bills during this period. Our care teams will be available to offer flexible payment options and can help find other solutions.

Another community partner stepping up to help our kids. Thank you MHC

Back for another year, our CNC machining students entered the Phillips Machinist CNC Machining competition! The objective is to make a part on a Haas CNC machine.

The school that places first wins an all expenses paid trip to California to see the Haas factory! Last year we made it into the top 10 and into the final round of judging (placing 4th overall)

Please take a few minutes: download the Phillips Machinist app on either Google Play for android or the App Store for iPhone, sign up for a free account, select competition on the main screen and then voting gallery to see the entries. VOTE FOR CA to get to CA!!

https://apps.apple.com/us/app/the-phillips-machinist/id1046408069

https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.phillipscorp.machinist&hl=en_US

post_text:
Boys Hoops beat Rams: Coxsackie-Athens 61, Rensselaer 57

RENSSELAER — Josh Kiefer drained three of four free throws in the closing second to ice Coxsackie-Athens’ 61-57 victory over Rensselaer in Tuesday’s Patroon Conference boys basketball game.

Renssleaer led 13-12 after one quarter, but a 21-11 second-quarter run put C-A on top 33-24 at halftime. The Rams pulled to within 48-40 by the end of the third quarter and kept it close in the final stanza, but Kiefer’s clutch free throws preserved the victory for the Indians.

Killian Schrader topped C-A with 22 points. Kiefer contributed 11 and Andon Roe had nine.

Samir Lockhart hit a game-high 25 for the Rams. Amani Nixon had 15 and Ramell Johnson 11.

COXSACKIE-ATHENS (61): Boehm 3-2-8, Kiefer 1-8-11, Roe 3-2-9, KAne Schrader 1-4-7, Killian Schrader 9-1-22, Simmons 2-0-4. Totals 19-17-61.

3-pointers: Killian Schrader 3, Kane Schrader, Roe, Kiefer.

RENSSELAER (57): Johnson 4-2-11, Lockhart 11-2-25, Nixon 5-2-15, Baker 0-0-0, Wright 2-1-6. Totals 22-7-57.

3-pointers: Nixon 3, Johnson, Lockhart, Wright.

via Daily Mail

post_text: Today we were notified that the police were in pursuit of an armed suspect known to be heading towards Catskill. As a precautionary measure, Edward J. Arthur Elementary School went into lock-out, a procedure where all exterior doors are locked to the public as well as first floor windows. During this time the school functioned as normal, students were able to move about the building, but were required to stay inside. In addition to our School Resource Officer, the NYS Police will be present during dismissal this afternoon.

post_text:
Voters approved the capital project proposal
170 YES
83 NO

The scope of the project includes :

Replacing approximately 50% of the 20 year old middle school roof
Installing back-up generators on both campuses to protect vital safety equipment, HVAC motors, refrigeration motors and technology servers and hardware from power surges, outages and brownouts.
Replace the 30 year old tennis courts and relocate them behind the press box parallel to the home bleachers.
Provide for additional exterior lighting on parts of our Coxsackie campus.

Thank you to everyone who voted.

Estimated timeline is for Final Design work to commence this winter with plans submitted to NYSED in the spring and work commencing next school year.
text:
Voters approved the capital project proposal
170 YES
83 NO

The scope of the project includes :

Replacing approximately 50% of the 20 year old middle school roof
Installing back-up generators on both campuses to protect vital safety equipment, HVAC motors, refrigeration motors and technology servers and hardware from power surges, outages and brownouts.
Replace the 30 year old tennis courts and relocate them behind the press box parallel to the home bleachers.
Provide for additional exterior lighting on parts of our Coxsackie campus.

Thank you to everyone who voted.

Estimated timeline is for Final Design work to commence this winter with plans submitted to NYSED in the spring and work commencing next school year.

College in the High School application form from CGCC for Spring offerings:
if you are taking a course through CGCC, please click on the link for the College in the High School application form: https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B6qrZo9MSPI_OXhSU1RhSmFKS2R2MG1hVS1TcVd1aktKcmpz/view?usp=sharing
If you are taking a course that offers college credit through CGCC and are interested in applying for credit, this application will need to be completed and handed in to Mrs. Weinstein by Friday, January 24th. CGCC NO LONGER ACCEPTS LATE APPLICATIONS so our deadline of the 24th has to be enforced to ensure all apps are complete and transcripts are prepared in time for their deadline of the 31st.
If you are in need of a hard copy application you can stop in to see Mrs. Weinsten in the HS Counseling Office. Your teacher will have some shortly, as well.

post_text: The Greene County Music Educators Association's Fall All County Music Festival will be held at Coxsackie-Athens Senior High School on Friday, November 8th. The concert, which will feature a Sr. High Jazz Band, an Elementary Chorus, a 7th-9th Grade Concert Band, and a 10th-12th Grade Chorus, will be held at 7:30 p.m. on Friday the 8th. Tickets will be sold at the door starting at 6:45 p.m.
